<% content_for :title, "Meetle" %>
<h2>So why don&rsquo;t you just meet me in the <strong>meetle</strong>?</h2>
<p>
  I just showed you a product I worked on for 15 years. Here's one I started just a few weeks ago in Rails.
  I hope it gives you a taste of my design thinking in mid-flight.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>The idea:</strong> Riffing off the saying &ldquo;This meeting could've been an email,&rdquo;
  the app receives emails and transforms them into web pages that your 
  &ldquo;attendees&rdquo; can respond to asynchronously.
  This gets rid of live meetings while also creating a better way to gather feedback than a lengthy reply chain would.
</p>
<p>
  I'm calling it <strong>Meetle</strong> right now. It's all running locally at the moment, so screenshots and video 
  captures will have to do!
</p>
<hr>
<h3>Sharpening tone and message</h3>
<p>
  Oftentimes, I'll start design with copy. It helps me evolve the idea into something real. Here's my current homepage design and copy.
</p>
<div class="figure-container">
  <figure>
    <%= image_tag "meetle-0.webp", alt: "A screenshot of the Meetle homepage." %>
    <figcaption>
      <span>
        <strong>The elevator pitch:</strong> In 30 seconds, I want someone to understand the idea,
        why it's useful, and entice them to view the sample.
      </span>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>
<p>
  I came up with six other headlines that I all liked. So, I created a small Stimulus controller to randomize
  the headlines on page load:
</p>
<ul class="headlines">
  <li>This meeting could've been <strike>an email</strike> a meetle.</li>
  <li>Little + meeting = meetle.</li>
  <li>Why don't you just meet me at the meetle?</li>
  <li>Meetles get everyone on the same (web) page.</li>
  <li>A meeting...without the meeting part.</li>
  <li>5.5 million meetings a day should've been meetles.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>Marketing through pricing</h3>
<p>
  Instead of a monthly subscription, I'm considering selling each meetle at a flat rate. 
  That not only provides a more clear price comparison (the true time cost of a meeting vs. a meetle), but also 
  an alternative selling angle: <strong>Buy a pack of meetles for someone else, like your meeting-loving manager</strong>!
</p>
